properties.name: Seattle Public Library (SPL), Central Library
properties.description: Opened in 1891 as a single reading room in Pioneer Square, the City’s public library system now includes 27 locations including the iconic Central branch, designed by Rem Koolhaas and Joshua Prince-Ramus.

properties.name: SPL, Ballard
properties.description: The branch has a nautical-themed green roof planted with native flora.

properties.name: SPL, Beacon Hill
properties.description: Eleven Beacon Hill-area writers and poets have haikus, prose, or fiction throughout the branch and outside on quarry rocks.

properties.name: SPL, Broadview
properties.description: This branch features four art pieces by Indigenous artist Marvin Oliver.

properties.name: SPL, Capitol Hill
properties.description: This branch features Iole Alessandrini's "Contour," a green, living wall over the entrance.

properties.name: SPL, Columbia
properties.description: This branch hosts regular readings with the African-American Writers’ Alliance.

properties.name: SPL, Delridge
properties.description: The branch anchors the first floor of a three-story apartment building.

properties.name: SPL, Douglass-Truth
properties.description: Named for Frederick Douglass and Sojourner Truth, the branch features the African-American Collection of Literature and History, as well as a “Soul Pole.”

properties.name: SPL, Fremont
properties.description: This branch opened in 1921 and has since been listed on the National Register of Historic Places and named a landmark building by Seattle's Landmarks Preservation Board.

properties.name: SPL, Green Lake
properties.address: 7364 E Green Lake Dr N, Seattle, WA 98115
properties.description: This branch was built in 1910 and is located across the street from Green Lake Park, which features a 2.8 mile walking trail around the lake.

properties.name: SPL, Greenwood
properties.description: The branch features glass art with images and texts inspired by Gilgamesh’s journey of self-discovery.

properties.name: SPL, High Point
properties.description: You can enjoy a view of Puget Sound from this branch’s meeting room.

properties.name: SPL, International District / Chinatown
properties.description: This branch is part of a community center that includes affordable housing, retail, and a gathering space. “Wellspring” by Rene Yung features tea cups from local residents.

properties.name: SPL, Lake City
properties.description: The building features bronze gates by renowned Seattle artist and sculptor George Tsutakawa.

properties.name: SPL, Madrona-Sally Goldmark
properties.description: Named for local activist Sally Goldmark, the building is a renovated fire station.

properties.name: SPL, Magnolia
properties.description: This branch was designed by noted architect Paul Hayden Kirk, with landscape design by Richard Haag. It features furniture by master craftsman George Nakashima.

properties.name: SPL, Montlake
properties.description: "Skylight Aperture Sundial" by Rebecca Cummins projects a series of colorful spotlights that move through the library throughout the day, as the sun appears to move across the sky.

properties.name: SPL, NewHolly
properties.description: The branch is housed within a "Campus of Learners" that includes a K-12 tutoring program, a jobs center, a branch of South Seattle Community College, and child care centers.

properties.name: SPL, Northeast
properties.description: The building was originally designed by the father of Northwest architectural modernism, Paul Thiry.

properties.name: SPL, Northgate
properties.description: A partnership between Seattle Parks & Recreation and the Library, this community hub is an urban gathering space across from the Northgate Mall.

properties.name: SPL, Queen Anne
properties.description: One of several “Carnegie” libraries in Seattle, this 1914 branch is listed on the National Register of Historic Places and is a  Seattle Landmarks Preservation Board landmark building.

properties.name: SPL, Rainier Beach
properties.description: “Memories'' by mixed-media artist Ariela Boronat, a former Rainier Beach resident, showcases photographs from community members on  cloth to highlight the delicacy of memory.

properties.name: SPL, South Park
properties.description: The study room features a community mural created by teen patrons and local artist Angelina Villalobos.

properties.name: SPL, Southwest
properties.description: Canadian artist Katherine Kerr’s “Anthology” shows five sets of bronze hands cast from patrons holding objects inspired by community members.

properties.name: SPL, University
properties.description: One of the oldest “Carnegie” libraries in Seattle, this branch began serving the public in 1910.

properties.name: SPL, Wallingford
properties.description: This branch shares space with social service organizations which creates a vibrant community hub.

properties.name: SPL, West Seattle
properties.description: Opened in July 1910, this location was the first permanent library branch to open in Seattle.
